@@yThreshold Post Ruins@@N~
The Threshold Post was once the administrative junction where mountain route-house governance ended and lowland civic authority began — a boundary seven times contested in formal legal proceedings.  What remains is a collapsed stone building of substantial construction, its walls cracked by frost and volcanic tremor, its interior exposed to sky where the roof fell in during an Ashfall-era ash-load event.  @@yWarden commission debris@@N covers the central platform: ledger fragments, overwritten schedule boards, a single iron signpost still bearing faded route designations for three passes.  The hub opens onto five distinct approaches, each heading toward a different regime of the mountain's interior, and experienced travelers stop here to orient before committing to any direction.  The @@r basalt footholds@@N and the chalk-ash traces of the Chalkwind Saddle approaches are both visible from this position.
