@@ySalvage Assessment House Forecourt@@N~
The forecourt of the Salvage Assessment House retains its formal layout despite decades of abandonment: a flagstoned entry yard, two crumbling pillars that once bore hanging seals of commercial authority, and a notice post where contested authority declarations are still nailed in overlapping layers.  The @@yKiess-funded Assessment House@@N operated here as a certification point for volcanic materials extracted from the upper range — mirror-quality obsidian, sulfur blooms, and pumice each required separate origin documentation before they could enter the lowland trade network.  The newest notice is older than any living warden, its ink faded to illegibility; the oldest is only a pressed impression in the wood where iron letters once spelled a Compact certification requirement.
