#6133
@@rBlack Basalt Ridge@@N~
The ridge crest exposes a stratum of @@r jet-black basalt@@N fractured into irregular columns by centuries of thermal cycling — the mountain's equivalent of a structural memory, each crack a record of a cycle the rock survived and reset.  The ashrunner warrens are visible in the shallow depressions between columns: tunnel openings the diameter of a cart wheel, their rims worn smooth by generations of passage, the substrate around them compacted and stained from years of nest-warming activity.  Sight lines from this position cover most of the lower foothills, and experienced travelers use the ridge as a waypoint for identifying weather and ash-column activity in the upper zones.  The terrain drops south toward the east fork road and north toward the higher ridges above.
