@@rScorched Pine Ridge@@N~
A line of charred cinderpine remnants marks the edge of an old lahar flow that stripped the eastern face of this ridge and left the surviving trees at its margin bleached white from heat exposure.  The lahar did not reach far enough to kill these pines outright — they were scorched rather than burned, and the subsequent regrowth around their bleached trunks creates a visual record of thermal injury and recovery that Keeper survey crews noted as a visible stratigraphy of eruptive events.  From this ridge, the Assessment House ruins are visible below and to the southwest, and the geometry of the lower foothold approaches becomes legible as a system rather than a tangle.  The rock underfoot is particularly stable here — the same thermal event that bleached the pines baked the substrate into a dense ceramic layer.
