@@yThermal Seep Ground@@N~
A warm-water seep emerges here through a fracture in the basalt bedrock, staining the rock face orange with iron mineral deposits that have built up over geological time into formations resembling arrested rust.  @@G Sulfur moss@@N — a thermophilic ground cover that indicates active geothermal conditions — carpets the wet margins of the seep in a vivid biological contrast to the dark volcanic substrate.  The water temperature is noticeably elevated compared to the surrounding runoff: warm enough to produce faint steam on cold mornings, warm enough that the ground immediately surrounding the seep never freezes.  The iron-sulfur chemistry of the water makes it undrinkable without filtration, a fact that the absence of animal tracks near the water confirms.
