The sink crust field is the most dangerous section of the Middle Fan crossing — @@y thin hardened crust@@N covers a network of gas-hollow pockets where internal pressure has separated the surface layer from the substrate below.  The crust is visually indistinguishable from solid fan surface but sounds hollow when struck, and yields unpredictably to concentrated weight.  The passable corridor through the field is narrow, following a route marked by extraction crews with embedded iron spikes at the crust edges — the spikes are still in place, their spacing indicating a path barely wide enough for a laden cart.  No creatures capable of sustained weight-bearing movement can function in the hollow-zone chemistry, where gas seep concentrations are at their most intense.
