#6367
@@rNull Cairn Field@@N~
The Null Cairn Field is the most symbolically complex site in the Cinderteeth — @@r a field of deliberately erased name-stones@@N standing in rows across a cleared basalt plateau, every stone blank, the original carved names removed by grinding rather than simply unmarked from the start.  The erasure was deliberate and formal: commission records document the "Null Cairn Order" as a legal remedy for a specific historical failure, the stones originally marking individuals whose names had been inscribed under commission authority through a procedure later ruled invalid, and the erasure ordered as correction rather than dishonor.  The blank stones bear secondary inscriptions added during the erasure process — "unknown" in three script traditions representing the three linguistic communities whose members are represented in the field: commission standard notation, Ridgekin symbolic script, and a third tradition identified as pre-Conclave mercantile shorthand.  The "unknown" designation was chosen specifically to distinguish the erasure from punishment: these persons' names were erased from a formal record not because they were condemned but because the record was itself illegal.  Some stones also carry a small carved mark below the "unknown" inscription — a circle with a single radial line, a symbol identified in Ventspeaker notation as meaning "witnessed" or "acknowledged," added by parties unknown at some point after the original erasure.
