#6455
@@rSeven Ash Arches — Approach@@N~
The approach to the Seven Ash Arches is where the transit cut through the ridge spur first becomes visible as a complete structure — @@r seven distinct arched openings@@N are visible in sequence, each framing the next, the successive arches creating a corridor effect that draws the eye through the entire cut at once from this vantage point.  The oldest arch is immediately apparent even from the approach: its stone is darkest and heaviest, its geometry simpler than those behind it, its profile worn rounder at the edges by more centuries of weather than any arch of comparable construction elsewhere in the Cinderteeth.  Each subsequent arch represents a rebuilding generation, and from the approach the layered construction history is readable like a text — the mortar color varies, the stone facing changes, the arch proportions shift between mathematical styles that the commission's architectural survey associated with different institutional periods.  The First Commission survey identified at least six distinct rebuilding phases, with the seventh arch the most recent, constructed using techniques and materials from the Conclave's era of Fold access.  The approach is level and well-maintained, the survey commission having cleared and regraded it as part of the transit infrastructure work that accompanied their geological survey operations.  A wooden post at the approach bearing the commission's survey notation CH-24 marks the formal beginning of the arch corridor.
