#6456
@@ySeven Ash Arches — First Arch@@N~
The First Arch is the oldest standing structure in the Seven Ash Arches corridor — @@y the stone here@@N is different from every subsequent arch: larger-cut blocks of a darker basalt, fitted with only minimal mortar in the joints, their weight providing structural stability that later builders could not replicate through technique alone.  The arch soffit bears burn-marks from the ash events that gave the structure its name, concentric scorch patterns that the commission's analysis attributed to a specific type of volcanic gas ignition rather than open flame.  Material from the First Arch's first collapse — a partial failure sometime in the mountain's pre-survey history — was deliberately incorporated into the foundation courses of the rebuilt span, giving the structure a continuous material connection to its own origin.
E
first arch construction~
The First Arch's construction pre-dates any documented activity in the Cinderteeth by several centuries — the commission estimated its original construction date at roughly four hundred years before the Ventspeaker period based on material weathering and the patina depth on the exposed surfaces.  The founding stones are each unique, shaped individually rather than cut to a standard, suggesting pre-institutional construction by a single skilled builder working without a formal workforce.  No name attaches to the first builder; the arch is simply here, older than the record of anyone who might have built it.
