@@ySeven Ash Arches — Fourth Arch@@N~
The Fourth Arch has a prominent crack running from the western haunch to the keystone, its path suggesting the arch settled differentially when the spur ridge shifted during a seismic event — @@y the crack is old@@N and fully stabilized, the structural assessment carved into the eastern pier face confirming that the commission's surveyors examined it and determined the arch sound despite its appearance.  The stabilization is evident: iron pins have been driven into the crack at intervals and backed with a grey mineral grout that has hardened to match the surrounding stone's compressive strength.  The commission's assessment notation on the pier includes a detailed description of the crack's geometry and their methodology for determining stability, making this arch one of the better-documented structural assessments in the entire Fold approach record.
E
structural assessment~
The commission's structural assessment notation on the fourth arch's pier reads as a practical tutorial in the methodology the survey team used throughout the Cinderteeth: crack width measurement at multiple points, comparison of current width to the stabilization record baseline, percussion testing of the surrounding stone for void presence, and examination of the grout line for water infiltration signs.  The methodology was developed specifically for the mountain environment where freeze-thaw cycles pose the primary ongoing structural threat.  The commission concluded that cracks of this type in properly stabilized masonry arches typically remain safe indefinitely unless the underlying ground movement resumes — the fourth arch crack has not moved in the time covered by commission records.
