The Seventh Arch is the final arch of the corridor, its span marking the formal end of the transit cut and the beginning of the open Western Fold approach zone beyond — @@y the arch@@N frames a view eastward into a landscape noticeably different from the Bellspine country behind: paler rock, compressed ridge formations, and a faint haze of geothermal gas that hangs over the lower terrain in settled weather.  The arch's keystone bears a carved inscription in the commission's notation system recording the arch as "the gateway of counted passages — seven times fallen, seven times rebuilt, seventh and standing."  The phrase is understood to refer to both the seven rebuilding generations of the arch corridor and the Ventspeaker tradition of counting the arch passage as a formal threshold act — crossing the seventh arch meant formally committing to the Fold approach.
E
seventh arch as threshold~
The Ventspeaker tradition of threshold passage through the seventh arch was documented by the commission's cultural survey team as one of the most well-preserved Ventspeaker ritual practices in the entire mountain range.  The practice involved a formal pause at the seventh arch's keystone, a declaration of purpose addressed to the vent spirits believed to monitor the passage, and a small offering of ash from the traveler's own fire placed at the eastern pier's base.  The commission found the offering accumulation at the eastern pier base to be substantial — centuries of ash deposits compacted into a layer several centimeters thick — and concluded that the practice had been maintained continuously from Ventspeaker founding through to the late Conclave period.
