#6462
@@yRed Sister Cistern Alpha@@N~
Red Sister Cistern Alpha is the larger of the two parallel cisterns, its outer walls of dressed volcanic tuff showing the characteristic Ventspeaker construction style — stepped outer courses tapering inward toward the top, with drainage channels carved at the base that connect to a sub-grade collection system — @@y the interior@@N is unexpectedly spacious, the cistern's filtration beds arranged in three descending tiers: coarse pumice on top, medium calcite aggregate in the middle, fine ash and mineral substrate at the base.  Spring water from the geothermal source enters through a sealed inlet pipe at the upper tier's east face and exits through a calibrated outflow at the base, the filtration chemistry converting the iron- and sulfur-heavy source water into a mineral-balanced output used by everyone who traveled this route.  The Conclave's modifications are visible in the iron pipe fittings at both inlet and outlet — replacement hardware installed over the original ceramic Ventspeaker fittings, which are partially visible around the pipe flanges.
E
filtration chemistry~
The three-tier pumice-calcite-ash filtration system represents a sophisticated understanding of sequential mineral chemistry: the pumice tier removes large particulates and provides initial biological filtering through its porous structure; the calcite tier neutralizes acidic compounds and precipitates dissolved iron; the fine-ash substrate removes sulfur compounds through adsorption.  The Ventspeaker designers apparently derived the filtration system from observation of natural spring filtration in the Fold's geological layers, replicating those layers in the artificial cistern context.  The commission's chemical testing confirmed that the output water met safe standards even after the Conclave's period of disuse, the filtration material having retained its function through centuries of periodic flow without maintenance.
~
