@@rRed Sister Cistern Beta@@N~
Red Sister Cistern Beta is the slightly smaller twin of Alpha, its outer construction nearly identical but with subtle differences in the drainage arrangement that reflect a different master builder — @@r Beta's drainage channels@@N run east-west rather than north-south, suggesting the second cistern was oriented to feed a different distribution point than its partner.  The interior filtration beds are the same three-tier arrangement as Alpha, but with different proportions: Beta uses a larger calcite tier and a thinner pumice tier, optimizing for the specific chemistry of its share of the source flow.  The cisterns were designed to share a single geothermal spring source split between them, giving the combined system greater total capacity than either individual cistern, and also providing redundancy — if one cistern's filtration beds needed replacement, the other could continue supplying the route.
E
great oasis cistern comparison~
The commission's hydrological survey compared the Red Sister Cisterns to the Great Oasis cistern system in the desert territories to the south, finding that the filtration chemistry approach was similar but the engineering contexts entirely different.  The Great Oasis cisterns manage surface water in an arid environment; the Red Sister Cisterns manage geothermal spring water in a volcanic mountain environment.  The commission's conclusion was that the two systems were developed independently, both deriving from the same first-principles observation of natural filtration geology, rather than one system representing knowledge transfer from the other.  The parallel development finding was one of the commission's more interesting comparative results, suggesting that the geological filtration approach was a natural discovery that multiple sophisticated engineering traditions arrived at independently.
~
