@@yRed Sister Cistern Filtration Chamber@@N~
The filtration chamber is the sub-grade level where both cisterns' drainage systems meet, their combined filtered output collecting in a common reservoir before distribution — @@y the chamber@@N is lower and more confined than the cisterns above, its ceiling the underside of the filtration bed floor with iron drainage grates visible overhead, and its walls lined with the iron-rich mineral deposits left by centuries of filtered water passage.  The mineral staining creates a dramatic visual effect: dark red and orange bands following the water flow paths down the walls, with pale calcite streaks where mineral-saturated water has dried at air exposure points.  The spring water input arrives through a sealed stone channel at the east end, its smell faintly sulfurous before the filtration layers remove the sulfur compound load, and the output exits through a large pipe at the west end toward the distribution point above the approach area.
E
geothermal spring input~
The spring that feeds the Red Sister Cisterns is a direct geothermal expression of the Western Fold's fault block geology — the water rises through a fissure in the fault block's lower structure, carrying dissolved minerals absorbed from the deep thermal rock.  The mineral load changes with the season: in winter the flow is lower and the sulfur concentration higher; in spring thaw the flow increases and the chemistry becomes more dilute.  The filtration system was calibrated for the higher-load winter chemistry, meaning it over-performs during spring runoff — the commission noted the spring output as one of the most reliable water sources in the entire Cinderteeth Mountain survey area, active year-round even when surface water sources in the approach zone are frozen.
~
