#6466
@@yVent Platform Site Alpha@@N~
The first Ventspeaker vent platform encountered on the Western Fold approach is a substantial structure — a raised stone stage built directly over a low-intensity fumarole vent, its surface elevated perhaps a meter above the surrounding terrain on dressed basalt courses — @@y the vent opening@@N at the stage's center is ringed with carved stone that channels the gas upward through the platform in a controlled exhaust, preventing accumulation under the stage floor.  The oracle stage occupies the highest point of the platform, a semicircular raised area with a carved stone seat facing east — toward the Fold interior — and flanked by two upright stones that frame the view of the Fold approach from the seated position.  The platform's construction shows sophisticated understanding of thermally stable substrate selection: the foundations are sunk below the frost line into compressed volcanic substrate that does not shift in freeze-thaw cycles, and the platform drainage is designed to prevent water infiltration into the vent channel.
E
vent platform construction~
Thermally stable substrate selection was a critical construction challenge for any permanent structure built over an active vent: the surrounding ground is subject to thermal expansion and contraction that causes ordinary foundations to heave and crack over time.  The Ventspeaker builders addressed this by founding vent platforms on compressed volcanic breccia deposits rather than open basalt, selecting construction sites where the breccia layer was at least two meters thick.  The commission found that every intact Ventspeaker vent platform in the Cinderteeth used this founding technique, confirming it as a deliberate, understood construction standard rather than an accidental feature of individual sites.
