@@rTiered Fire-Pit Site Alpha@@N~
The first tiered fire-pit site is the most complex ritual combustion structure on the Western Fold approach — @@r three concentric rings@@N of fitted stone, each ring lower than the one inside it, creating a graduated combustion platform where material at different tiers burns at different rates controlled by the tier's elevation relative to the prevailing wind.  The ash layer visible throughout the site is substantial — the commission's stratigraphic section through the deposit revealed twenty-three distinct combustion events of varying intensity, with the most recent layer at depth indicating that the site's last active use predated the Conclave's occupation of the Fold.  No evidence of Conclave use of this site was found; unlike the vent platforms, which the Conclave repurposed for equipment staging, the fire-pits appear to have been deliberately avoided by the Conclave's personnel, possibly because the ritual combustion was associated with Ventspeaker practices they found doctrinally problematic.
E
stratigraphic dating~
The commission's stratigraphic analysis of fire-pit ash deposits used two techniques: visual identification of chemically distinct ash layers (different combustion materials produce different mineral residues), and radiocarbon analysis of partially carbonized organic material recovered from the deeper layers.  The technique confirmed that the lowest, oldest combustion event at Site Alpha occurred during the earliest identified Ventspeaker period, and that combustion events continued at irregular intervals through the entire Ventspeaker era before ending abruptly at a level corresponding to the Conclave's arrival.  The abrupt end of combustion at the Conclave transition layer at both fire-pit sites was one of several lines of evidence the commission used to document the discontinuity between Ventspeaker and Conclave occupation of the Western Fold.
