@@rWestern Fold Entry@@N~
The Western Fold Entry is the first room of the Western Fold proper — @@r the downthrown fault block@@N is now fully expressed in the landscape: the terrain is measurably lower than the ridgelines visible on both flanks, the enclosed basin geometry creating an overhead sky that is narrower than on the approach, the flanking walls rising more steeply than any terrain since the Bellspine's eastern corridors.  The heat is now unambiguous rather than gradually increasing — the rock surfaces emit warmth continuously, the air is thick with mineral-saturated moisture, and the thermophilic biological communities that carpet the Fold's surfaces are visible immediately on every rock face that has been wet for any sustained period.  Iron-red bacterial mats, pale fungal threads branching through rock cracks, and occasional clusters of heat-adapted lichen create a living veneer over the geological surfaces that gives the Fold its distinctive visual signature — simultaneously volcanic and organic in a way that distinguishes it sharply from the sterile mineral character of the approach zones.  The Ash Cult's territorial marking is everywhere: painted symbols on every flat surface, carved phrases on projecting rocks, and at the entry point itself a carved arch of doctrinal text that frames passage into the Fold as a formal act of submission to the cult's proclaimed authority.  Commission survey notation CH-37 is still visible beneath a layer of cult paint, the underlying notation recording the entry point's position and thermal measurements that the cult overwriting has not entirely obscured.
E
downthrown fault block expression~
The Western Fold's downthrown character is most apparent at the entry, where the change from approach corridor to enclosed basin floor is most abrupt.  A downthrown fault block is a section of crust that has subsided along fault lines relative to its surroundings; in the Cinderteeth's case the Fold's floor sits approximately forty meters below the adjacent ridge crests, a subsidence that occurred in the mountain's ancient tectonic history and that has been maintained by the ongoing geothermal activity keeping the Fold warm enough that erosion and deposition do not fill it in.  The enclosed geometry that results — basin floor surrounded by elevated ridges — is both geologically unusual in the region and physically distinctive to travelers, who immediately sense the changed topology even before the thermal and chemical differences register.
~
