@@yThermophilic Fungal Growth Zone@@N~
The thermophilic fungal growth zone north of the Fold floor's central expanse is the densest concentration of heat-adapted biological communities in the Western Fold — @@y the rock surfaces here@@N are almost entirely carpeted with fungal networks, their hyphae forming visible mat layers over the basalt and their fruiting bodies emerging at intervals in forms that appear, from any distance, like miniature architectural structures: towers, plates, conical extrusions.  The color palette is distinctive: orange, red-brown, pale yellow, and occasional bright white patches where different fungal communities occupy different thermal niches on the same rock face, each community positioned within its preferred temperature range.  The growth zone is biologically complex and visually dramatic, and its resemblance to the Withered Depths' corrupted root-fungal networks has created genuine scholarly confusion about the relationship between the two systems.
E
withered depths scholarly confusion~
The thermophilic fungal networks of the Western Fold are biologically and ecologically entirely distinct from the corrupted blight-networks of the Withered Depths, but their visual similarity has confused multiple research expeditions.  The Fold networks are natural thermophiles: organisms whose ancestors have occupied geothermal environments for geological time, their physiology optimized for heat and mineral-rich geothermal fluids.  The Withered Depths networks are corrupted ordinary mycorrhizal fungi, their physiology distorted by abandoned Prism Thesis crystal resonance implants left in the forest's root junction nodes.  The institutional origin connection — Prism Thesis crystal techniques were developed in the Western Fold before deployment in the forests south of the Cinderteeth — makes the visual confusion understandable but does not make it less erroneous.  Commission report volume nine contains a definitive comparative biological survey separating the two systems, required reading for any research party intending to work in both areas.
~
