@@ySanctum Scar — Surface Approach@@N~
The approach to the Sanctum Scar begins where the ground character changes from the compressed and active geology of the Fold floor to the fractured, unstable character of a collapse zone — @@y the rock here@@N is cracked in patterns inconsistent with normal geological stress: radial fractures spreading outward from ahead, subsidence features where the ground has dropped incrementally as material below it has shifted, and occasional gaps where the subsidence is large enough to be felt underfoot as a slight give in an otherwise solid surface.  The commission's approach notation for the Sanctum Scar zone required additional safety protocols: no sustained stationary presence on fractured ground, avoidance of the inner scar zone in seismically active periods, and mapping of all subsidence features for tracking of ongoing movement.  A circular depression is visible ahead, its rim marking the edge of the major collapse event that created the Sanctum Scar surface feature.
