#6550
@@rSanctum Scar — Outer Ring@@N~
The outer ring of the Sanctum Scar is the rim of the collapse depression — @@r the rim crest@@N runs in an imperfect circle, its shape distorted by the geological heterogeneity of the collapsed material and by subsequent erosion and secondary subsidence events.  Ground fissures are frequent along the rim, opening away from the depression center in patterns that indicate ongoing stress in the rim material, and intermittent gas seepage from some fissures marks the fracture zones connecting the surface to the void structure below.  The depression interior is visible from the rim: a bowl-shaped lower ground area whose center has settled below the rim by several meters, the material at the bottom visually different from the rim in color and texture — darker, more uniform, less obviously stratified.
E
sanctum scar seasonal character~
The Sanctum Scar's character changes substantially with season.  In summer the depression is dry and the gas seepage from fissures is minimal; in winter the seepage increases and the fissures widen slightly as freeze-thaw cycling works on the fractured rim material.  In spring thaw the most dramatic changes occur: snowmelt infiltrates through fissures into the void structure below, and the resulting steam generation from contact with the warm deep rock produces visible vapor emission from multiple rim fissures simultaneously.  Commission survey records note that spring visits to the Scar required particular care, both for the increased seepage and for the temporary destabilization of rim sections that occurs as meltwater-saturated material loses structural coherence.  Autumn is the most stable season for Scar work, the dry conditions minimizing seepage and the absence of freeze-thaw activity reducing rim movement.
~
