@@ySanctum Scar — Inner Zone@@N~
The inner zone of the Sanctum Scar is the depression floor — @@y the collapsed material forming the floor@@N has a different texture from the rim's native geology, its components being the rubble of the upper structure that fell into the void space during the collapse event: broken masonry fragments mixed with geological debris in proportions that confirm the presence of a substantial built structure below the surface before the collapse.  Occasional subsidence events occur here — the floor drops suddenly by a few centimeters at localized points when unsupported material below gives way — creating a dynamic ground environment that the commission's safety protocols addressed with explicit protocols about spacing and timing of survey personnel movement.  The central collapse feature at the inner zone's deepest point is a direct access shaft to the structural void below.
E
sanctum scar collapse scale and history~
The Sanctum Scar collapse event that created the current depression is distinct from the ongoing subsidence: the commission's stratigraphic analysis determined that the main collapse occurred in a single event of short duration, creating the depression's basic shape, while subsequent subsidence has gradually deepened and extended the depression over the centuries since the main event.  The main collapse is estimated to have occurred approximately three hundred years before the commission's survey, based on weathering of the collapse scar edges and dating of material deposited in the depression after the collapse.  The scale of the collapse — the depression is approximately forty meters in diameter and eight meters deep at center — indicates the void below is substantial, and the masonry fragments in the collapse debris confirm that the upper portions of the Sunken Sanctum's structure were destroyed or severely compromised in the collapse event.  The commission's geological analysis concluded that the lower portions of the Sunken Sanctum, below the collapse zone, could remain structurally intact if built in the Fold's competent lower basalt layer.
~
