The Upper Mountain Gate is the threshold between the mid-range terrain of the Western Fold approach and the upper Crown approaches — @@r the gate@@N is not a constructed feature but a geological inevitability: the point where the mountain's topology demands acknowledgment that everything below has been preparation for what lies above.  The rock changes character abruptly: from the compressed, thermally saturated character of the Western Fold's fault block to the fractured, vitrified character of rock that has been heated, cracked, cooled, reheated, and subjected to the physical violence of volcanic activity at close range for geological time.  At night the caldera glow is visible from this gate position — not bright enough to cast shadows but bright enough to be unmistakable, a reddish emanation from the direction of the Firsttooth's summit that confirms you are in the territory of an active volcano.  The commission's survey documentation notes this as the position where standard geological survey protocols were replaced by volcanic environment protocols, requiring additional safety equipment, mandatory partner systems, and strict time limits on summit approach work.  The gate is the last position where retreat to the Western Fold is straightforward; above and beyond it, the terrain commits travelers to the Crown environment with all its hazards.
