#6599
@@yVent-Gas Inversion Pocket Alpha@@N~
The first vent-gas inversion pocket is a shallow depression in the Crown terrain where heavier-than-air volcanic gases pool in still weather — @@y the pocket is indistinguishable from the surrounding terrain@@N in appearance: same rock surfaces, same scree character, no visible gas emission, no discoloration that would alert an observer to its character.  The hazard is the invisible gas layer at the pocket floor, a colorless odorless high-concentration zone that is detectable only at the earliest stage of approach by the faint sweet-sulfur odor the commission described as "arriving before the concentration becomes dangerous — by approximately one meter at normal walking pace in still conditions."  The commission placed hazard stakes at the pocket rim with red flags and explicit gas detection instructions.
E
gas inversion detection protocol~
The commission's detection protocol for vent-gas inversion pockets was developed after the first unwarned encounter with this site, in which a commission team member experienced significant dizziness before retreating.  The protocol: approach any depression in Crown terrain with one lead person extended arm-length ahead of the group; if the lead person notices any sweet-sulfur odor, all personnel stop and the lead person retreats; test-drop a handful of scree fragments into the depression and observe their behavior (gas concentration causes slight condensation visible on cold fragments in the right lighting); stake the pocket rim for future reference.  The protocol's requirement for a lead person ahead of the group reflects the fact that the safety margin between first detection and dangerous concentration is approximately one meter at still-air conditions and depends entirely on wind direction and speed — in crosswind conditions the pocket may be safe; in still conditions it must be treated as an active hazard.
