#6604
@@rWidow's Spire — Summit@@N~
The Widow's Spire summit is the highest stable observation point in the Cinderteeth Mountains, its position on the Spire's ancient basalt column placing it above the surrounding debris field and providing an unobstructed panoramic view that no position in the active Crown terrain can match — @@r the summit view@@N encompasses all three principal peaks of the Ember Crown, the Firsttooth's active caldera glow visible even in daylight as a reddish-orange staining of the smoke above the summit, the Secondtooth's lower profile with its synchronized tremor rhythm readable as occasional shudders of the rock surface underfoot, and the far view of the Widow's Spire's own fallen structure on the Crown's northern face.  The Western Fold depression is visible below and to the west, its enclosed character apparent from above as a distinct lower area among the surrounding ridgelines, the thermophilic community's orange-red coloration visible as a subtle warm tint on the basin floor.  To the northeast the Great Northern Forest is visible on clear days as a dark-green expanse stretching to the horizon, its closest edge precisely at the altitude where the Crown's volcanic influence gives way to the forested lowland that characterizes the GNF's northwestern approach.  The Cinderteeth Mountains' full west-to-east extent is visible from this summit, from the contested foothills where the first route markers were placed to the upper Crown where nothing is maintained by any institution still operating.  The commission considered the summit view the finest single perspective on the entire mountain survey area, noting in their photographic log that the only difficulty was carrying the camera equipment to the top.
E
summit sightline catalog~
The commission's sightline catalog from the Widow's Spire summit documented eleven named reference points visible in favorable conditions.  Looking north: the northern ridge arm of the Cinderteeth, the GNF Northwestern Crown treeline, and the distant suggestion of the higher GNF interior.  Looking east: the northeastern ridge system connecting to the GNF border, the three GNF linking ridges (from which the survey team could see smoke from the GNF's northern ranger station on clear days).  Looking south: the Glasswash Fan scarp in the middle distance, the Forest of Confusion visible in the far south as a grey-green haze, and on exceptional days the distant geometry of the desert regions south of the forest.  Looking west: the saddle pass approaches, the lower foothills, and on the clearest days the boundary markers of the Roc Road route that the Kiess expeditions used.  The catalog provides a comprehensive orientation for anyone reaching the summit and constitutes one of the most practical pieces of survey documentation the commission produced.
~
