#6611
@@yCrown Scree — Lightning Hazard Zone@@N~
The lightning hazard zone in the Crown scree is where the ash column above the Firsttooth's active vent creates persistent static buildup conditions that increase lightning discharge probability significantly above background — @@y large ash columns@@N are electrically active, their particle interactions generating charge accumulation that discharges to ground at intervals, and the Crown's exposed scree provides the ground with minimal intervening structure.  Commission protocols required metal equipment stowage and low-profile positions when the ash column exceeded a specified height, the threshold based on documented static discharge events.  A lightning-grounded discharge to nearby metal has specific characteristics: a warning crackling sound approximately three seconds before the main discharge, a distinctive ozone smell, and occasional hair-standing static that provides additional warning time.
E
lightning-grounded ash column discharge~
The phenomenon of lightning grounding through the ash column to surface metal was documented in three commission incidents during the Crown survey, all involving equipment rather than personnel due to the commission's strict low-profile protocol compliance.  The largest discharge event destroyed a metal tripod and its mounted instrument, the discharge traveling down the tripod from the instrument head to the ground anchor, volatilizing the instrument housing and leaving a characteristic carbon trace on the rock surface at the base.  The commission's analysis found that the ash column's charge buildup was predictable with sufficient observation time — specific visual characteristics of column density and structure predicted elevated discharge risk — and that the observation-based prediction protocol reduced the surprise element sufficiently to allow planned equipment stowage rather than reactive emergency stowage.  The commission's lightning protocol was adopted in modified form by the Kiess extraction licensing system for all Crown operations.
~
