@@REmber Crown Entry@@N~
The Ember Crown Entry is the threshold where the geological character of the upper mountain approach gives way to the caldera zone proper — @@R the ground beneath your feet@@N radiates heat through boot leather in a way that earlier zones only suggested, a low constant warmth that confirms proximity to subsurface magma activity at a scale that the Cinderteeth's lower zones do not approach.  The rock surface here has changed from the mixed basalt-and-scree of the Crown approaches to a dense, dark, heat-sintered material whose surface texture is slightly glazed: fused by repeated thermal cycling at temperatures high enough to partially melt the outer stone layer, then cooled and reheated in cycles that have produced a ceramic-like skin over older rock.  Persistent glow-vent illumination is visible ahead — the permanent low-level volcanic gas emission from vents higher on the caldera face catches the thermal radiation from below and produces a faint orange-red glow that makes the upper caldera interior visible at night without any additional light source.  The commission's survey protocol for Ember Crown entry included mandatory thermal-gear inspection at this point: gloves rated for sustained contact with heated rock, boot reinforcement against heat conduction, and facial protection against gas-emission proximity events.  The zone north of this entry is rated for parties with full thermal expedition equipment — unequipped approach is documented in commission records as having produced casualties before the safety protocols were established.  The Upper Crown Junction connects below through the thermal shaft, and the Firsttooth lower caldera face rises to the north.
