@@rFirsttooth Mid-Caldera Face@@N~
The mid-caldera face of the Firsttooth is where the geological survey commission's mineral collection teams focused their ferric scoria sampling — @@r ferric scoria@@N is the volcanic rock product formed when lava rich in iron compounds is rapidly quenched by exposure to cold air, producing a rust-red to dark-orange porous matrix whose surface oxidation pattern is visually striking and whose mineral content makes it a subject of ongoing geological interest.  The mid-face elevation provides a clear view both downslope to the entry zone and upslope toward the caldera rim, the perspective making visible the full scale of the Firsttooth's structure — a cone that rises above its surroundings with the self-contained authority of a primary volcanic feature.  Commission survey records note that the mid-caldera face is where the most dramatic color transition occurs: the dark glazed rock of the lower face gives way to the orange-red scoria matrix that characterizes the active upper caldera zones.
E
ferric scoria formation~
Ferric scoria is distinguished from ordinary basalt scoria by its characteristic rust-orange to deep red coloration, the product of iron oxidation at high temperature during rapid cooling.  The specific color of ferric scoria indicates the oxidation state of the iron at the time of quenching: bright orange indicates full oxidation to ferric iron compounds, dark red indicates partial oxidation with mixed ferrous-ferric states, and the black streaks visible through some samples indicate iron sulfide formation where sulfur-rich gases were incorporated during solidification.  The commission's mineral classification identified the Firsttooth's mid-caldera scoria as unusually uniform in composition, suggesting a consistent lava chemistry across the most recent eruptive cycle that produced this surface layer.
~
