@@REmber Throne Inner Caldera Chamber@@N~
The Ember Throne Inner Caldera Chamber is the enclosed interior of the Firsttooth caldera at its geological core — @@R the chamber's ceiling@@N is the underside of the caldera rim structure, a geological vault whose scale is determined by the diameter of the primary eruption event that hollowed this space.  The Ember Throne itself is visible from this chamber: a basalt formation rising from the chamber floor that has accumulated volcanic minerals over eruption cycles into a structure whose scale and complexity has given it the quality of a cathedral form — not constructed, but grown, layer by layer, cycle by cycle, into a shape that different civilizations encountering it have independently interpreted as a throne.  The thermal environment of this chamber is the most extreme in the Cinderteeth range: temperature, pressure, and gas emission levels all exceed anything encountered in the approach zones, and the commission's survey noted that extended exposure without thermal protection produces physiological effects beginning at a duration far shorter than the approach zones require.  The geological activity of this chamber is continuous: fumarolic emissions from the floor vents, mineral crystallization on the walls as thermal gradients drive supersaturation, and the persistent subsonic pulse of the magma chamber below.  The sanctum gate to the Ember Throne antechamber is set into the north wall — a geological feature that appears to be a natural rock arch that has been worked, its edges dressed to a precise fit that produces an almost airtight seal against the thermal pressure differential.
E
sanctum gate~
The sanctum gate is a geological arch whose natural form has been worked by craftspeople whose tools and methods the commission's archaeological observer could not confidently identify: the arch's natural basalt has been dressed to precise tolerances, its edges shaped with a smoothness inconsistent with the thermal-modification tools documented in Ash Cult material culture.  The commission observer's notes suggest that the gate's working predates the current Ash Cult organization by several organizational generations — that whoever shaped it was not the current Cult but an earlier culture that occupied the Ember Crown at a period the current Cult does not document.  The keystone of the arch bears a carved inscription in a script the commission observer could not match to any documented regional writing system.
