#6675
@@ySummit Pumice Field@@N~
The Summit Pumice Field is an upper-layer deposit of pumice from the Firsttooth's most recent eruptive cycle — @@y the pumice here@@N is visually and texturally distinct from the lower-zone deposits: the vesicular structure is more uniform, the bubble distribution finer, and the silica content higher, all indicators of a more violent eruption event with rapid cooling that trapped more gas in a finer foam structure.  The commission's geological team identified the Summit Pumice Field as the finest-quality filtration-grade pumice in the Cinderteeth range, its vesicular quality superior for the water-filtration applications that make Cinderteeth pumice commercially significant.  The field extends east from the Ember Crown Entry and north into the caldera scree zone above.
E
summit pumice quality~
The differentiation between summit pumice and lower-zone pumice depends on the eruption event's characteristics: summit pumice derives from the highest-energy events where magma is fragmented under extreme pressure at the vent and ejected with sufficient force to cool rapidly in the upper air column.  The resulting vesicle structure is fine-grained and uniform, with bubble diameters averaging two to three millimeters and total porosity in the seventy to eighty percent range — significantly higher than the forty to sixty percent typical of lower-zone material.  The commission's sample set from this field was classified as premium filtration grade, suitable for precision filtration applications requiring consistent pore characteristics.
~
