#6676
@@yHigh Sulfur Bloom Deposit@@N~
The High Sulfur Bloom Deposit is the largest concentration of fresh sulfur crystal accumulation in the Cinderteeth range — @@y the crystals@@N here are freshly deposited, their pale yellow surface unmarked by the weathering that reduces older sulfur formations to the grey-white chalky material visible at lower elevations.  The commission's alchemical resource survey rated this deposit as premium quality, the crystal purity and quantity exceeding any other documented sulfur source in the range, with commercial extraction potential sufficient to justify the expedition cost if the thermal protection requirements for summit access could be reliably met.  The bloom formation is actively growing: the commission observer recorded crystal dimensions and estimated a deposition rate consistent with continuous fumarolic sulfur output from the caldera system above.
E
sulfur crystal quality~
Sulfur crystal quality for alchemical purposes depends on purity, crystal size, and formation context.  The Summit Bloom deposit's crystals are remarkable on all three metrics: the fumarolic condensation mechanism that deposits them produces high-purity sulfur by a natural fractional distillation process, with impurities remaining in the vapor phase while pure sulfur condenses on cooler rock surfaces at the deposit elevation.  Crystal size in this deposit ranges from centimeter-scale individual formations up to multi-centimeter clusters where undisturbed growth has continued over multiple deposition cycles.
